  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Stages:\n- Originated from efforts to combat organized crime and drug trafficking\n- Initial focus was on tracking financial transactions to identify criminal proceeds\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States:\n- First comprehensive anti-money laundering legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against Illicit Drug Trafficking\n- Established international framework for criminalizing money laundering\n- Promoted international cooperation in tracking financial crimes\n\n4. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - 1989:\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created comprehensive recommendations for national regulatory systems\n- Established global guidelines for financial transparency\n\n5. Significant Expansion Post-9/11:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Expanded scope to include terrorism financing\n\n6. Ongoing Global Developments:\n- Continuous refinement of international legal frameworks\n- Increasing focus on digital currency and cryptocurrency transactions\n- More sophisticated tracking and enforcement mechanisms",
